## Explicitly reject the current first-N pair method

Add this under `Rejected Mainlines` or `Candidate Sources`:

```text
Rejected: legal-order first-N pair scoring as candidate selection

A pair selector must not generate candidates by walking legal rows in nested
loop order and stopping at max_pairs. That method is deterministic and simple,
but it is biased toward early legal-row anchors and can miss important pairs
whose cells occur later in the legal table. It is allowed only as a unit-test
baseline or diagnostic smoke test.

The final pair scorer may score a supplied pair row set. It must not define
that set by first-N legal-order enumeration in normal runtime.
```

This matters because the current branch’s pair scoring path does exactly that: it walks legal rows in nested-loop order and stops once `max_pairs` is reached. That is a scoring scaffold, not a good candidate selector. 

